results.notes: These are a common find during the summer months when we get enough rain. It has stuffed white pores that change to yellow as it opens and darkens to an olivaceous color when old. The cap color is some shade of brown, ranging from dark brown to light tan depending on age and exposure to sun.The cap and stem flesh does not stain inside or out. The stipe is generally white with some specimens in the same group having a tan color and most having some fine reticulation on the stipe generally on the upper portion of the stipe. It would appear that they prefer oaks but I do find them growing near pine in sandy soil and I find most growing out in the grass away from the trees.

results.notes:
Multiple fruiting bodies at different stages of development growing in moss under old oaks. There were two clusters of 3 fbs each, one group of 2 fbs and several single basidiomata scattered around in the close vicinity of each other. I have not seen this species at this location before despite visiting it every year for the last 10 years.
The sole collected specimen was allowed to have its cap expand upon my return home. Eventually, the partial veil broke off the cap edges and collapsed on the floor. It was soft, moist and somewhat sticky to touch. The cap eventually produced a spore print and the spores were found to be consistent with ravenellii/rhopalopus (x400, no mounting agent). Exact measurements at x1000 TBD.

DNA Sequencing Results & Discussion (posted on 14-Feb-21):
> A contiguous nrLSU sequence of 1369 bps was obtained by Dr. Kudzma from two forward reads and posted to this observation. The reads overlap in the middle for ~300 bps to give the so called joined contig; the overlapping segment is an example of consensus contig. Unlike its often the case with nrITS, its not possible to get a full-length consensus sequence for LSU with just two reads due to the length of the amplified span of DNA from the start of the locus to the LR7 primer area (usually ~1450 bps long!). Since all reads gradually begin to lose resolution after 600 bps (due to broadening of peak shapes), legible spans of >800-900 bps from single reads are uncommon. However, if individual reads are of good quality, joined contigs are a perfectly satisfactory result.
> A BLASTn-250 of the first 922 bps, the most commonly sequenced region of nrLSU (upstream of the LR5 primer area), gave Rod Tulloss (RETs) accession of Amanita rhopalopus (HQ539733) as the top hit at 98.6% similarity. Alignment of the two sequences is shown in Fig. 1.1 The four ambiguities in MO417518 are not real mismatches and can be ignored. Strangely, the remaining 11 mismatching positions come from a short stretch of DNA the middle in the sequence, and are closely spaced the first and last mismatches are only 30 characters apart. Five of these appear to be part of variable-length repeating motifs, e.g., ATAT or TTTT, and can probably be dismissed, as well. The remaining differences notwithstanding, I am inclined to believe that the two sequences represent one species rather than two closely related taxa.
The second top-scoring hit in the BLAST report is also an accession labeled as Amanita rhopalopus, AF097393, at 97.8% similarity (see Fig. 2). I think its the same species, too. The sequence clearly has some problems due to the presence of a large number of positions labeled as N, which means it can be any base (up to 4 overlapping peaks); unresolved heterogeneity is likely the issue. Heteromorphy is a very common problem in the ribosomal loci in Lepidella, especially in ITS. Following these two hits, % similarity drops to <95%.
> A distance P-tree was built using selected accessions from the BLASTn and posted here as Fig. 3. Amanita rhopalopus appears as a member of sect. Roanokenses of subgenus Amanitina. The vast bulk of mycorrhizal lepidellas wound up in this section following the dismantling of the polyphyletic Amanita sect. Lepidella sensu Bas (1969) by Cui et al. (2018).2 Its interesting that Amanita ravenelii, a look-alike of A. rhopalopus, is a member of sect. Strobiliformes in the Cui et al. study. To date, this section contains a just a handful of mycorrhizal lepidellas, but will likely grow in size as more lepidellas are sequenced. The sole LSU accession of A. ravenelii in GenBank, MH486796, is derived from RETs voucher. It is only 90% similar to that of MO417518, and didnt appear in the BLASTn search because of the lower % similarity; its the one used in the Cui et al. study. Sections Validae and Phalloideae appear as monophyphyletic groups in Fig. 3.
